04348nam a22005175i 9780822398523DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223985237 a10.1515/97808223985232doi  a(DE-B1597)552002  a(OCoLC)1061868651  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0360102bisacsh04a975.5/425202/0747552211 aHandler, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New History in an Old Museum :bCreating the Past at Colonial Williamsburg /cEric Gable, Richard Handler. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b18 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 The New History in an Old Museum -- t2 Imag[in]ing Colonial Williamsburg -- t3 Why History Changes, or, Two Theories of History Making -- t4 Just the Facts -- t5 Social History on the Ground -- t6 The Company Line: Aspects of Corporate Culture at Colonial Williamsburg -- t7 The Front Line: Smile Free or Die -- t8 Picket Lines -- t9 The Bottom Line -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe New History in an Old Museum is an exploration of "historical truth" as presented at Colonial Williamsburg. More than a detailed history of a museum and tourist attraction, it examines the packaging of American history, and consumerism and the manufacturing of cultural beliefs. Through extensive fieldwork-including numerous site visits, interviews with employees and visitors, and archival research-Richard Handler and Eric Gable illustrate how corporate sensibility blends with pedagogical principle in Colonial Williamsburg to blur the lines between education and entertainment, patriotism and revisionism.During much of its existence, the "living museum" at Williamsburg has been considered a patriotic shrine, celebrating the upscale lifestyles of Virginia's colonial-era elite. But in recent decades a new generation of social historians has injected a more populist and critical slant to the site's narrative of nationhood. For example, in interactions with museum visitors, employees now relate stories about the experiences of African Americans and women, stories that several years ago did not enter into descriptions of life in Colonial Williamsburg. Handler and Gable focus on the way this public history is managed, as historians and administrators define historiographical policy and middle-level managers train and direct front-line staff to deliver this "product" to the public. They explore how visitors consume or modify what they hear and see, and reveal how interpreters and craftspeople resist or acquiesce in being managed. By deploying the voices of these various actors in a richly textured narrative, The New History in an Old Museum highlights the elements of cultural consensus that emerge from this cacophony of conflict and negotiation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh1 aGable, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398523zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398523.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles